        <TextView
            android:layout_width="wrap_content"
            android:layout_height="wrap_content"
            android:textAppearance="?android:attr/textAppearanceSmall"
            android:text="          1.	Holography is a technique for obtaining three dimensional optical image of the object. \n          2.	This is based on the phenomenon of the interference of light. \n          3.	In holography both the amplitude and the phase of wave is recorded. \n          4.	These amplitude and phase are stored in the interference pattern which is formed between the object wave and the reference wave. \n          5.	Interfering waves must be coherent. \n          6.	A light from the laser source splits in two beams. One beam will directly go to the object and then towards the photographic plate, while the other beam will go to the photographic plate after getting reflected from the mirror. \n          7.	At the photographic plate a beam reaching from the object is known as object beam or object wave where as the beam reflecting from the mirror and further reaching to the photographic plate is known as reference beam or reference wave. \n          8.	At the point of photographic plate, interference takes place between the object wave and the reference wave. \n          9.	After developing the photographic plate the plate is known as hologram. \n   "
            android:id="@+id/textView172"
            android:layout_alignParentStart="true"
            android:layout_below="@+id/textView171"
